&quot;PRINCESS CHIMAY DIES IN HOME HERE; The Former Mrs. Rutherfurd Stuyvesant Aided Charity Drive in 1st World War&quot;
from NYT of July 11, 1948  (needs subscription)
<a href="http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40811F63F59157A93C3A8178CD85F4C8485F9" rel="nofollow">select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40811F63F59157A...</a>
   &quot;During the first World War, the former Mrs. Stuyvesant was treasurer of the American Fund for the Charite Meternelle [sic] de Paris.&quot;  Rutherfurd Stuyvesant was already dead by that time. {Note: the correct name for the charity is Charite Maternelle de Paris.}

From <a href="http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&amp;GRid=21850289" rel="nofollow">www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&amp;GRid=21850289</a>
&quot;Matilda Elizabeth Loewenguth was the daughter of Joseph Loewenguth of Herrenwald, Alsatla. She was the widow of a Dutch Count. Countess Matilde Elizabeth De Wassanaer (nee Matilde Lowenguth) married Rutherfurd Stuyvesant on 6/16/1902. She was his second wife, as his first wife, Mary Pierrepont (married 1863) died (during childbirth) in 1897 without children&quot;

There is plenty more information in her Find-a-Grave record
an at her husband's: <a href="http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&amp;GRid=14841584" rel="nofollow">www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&amp;GRid=14841584</a>
